I only see one person on the core team that identifies and uses the same pronouns as me (At least publicly).

How can we change the community to be more welcoming to diversity? If there was a more diverse team I would be far more likely to feel comfortable contributing.

I've long dreamed about contributing to Rails since I became a developer. But over the last year or two I've long felt uncomfortable and not safe to contribute to Rails while DHH is involved.

(This isn't meant to slight the rest of the core team, y'all are lovely and I'm sorry)

You may be sitting there thinking "not all of that seems necessary", and I wish it wasn't... But for me, but this is what I *needed* to continue living. Maybe in ~5-10 years I'll have saved up enough money to afford the surgeries I need.
So yeah, if you're not trans, and someone tells you your company should help cover trans related costs, listen to them.

I'm one of the lucky ones to have means to make ends meet and still pay for all this. You know what this doesn't leave a lot of room for? Any surgeries I medically *need*. This is why insurance is such a big deal for so many trans people.

You wanna know what it costs me to simply *exist*?

$350/mo - Laser payment, ~8.1k left on this.
$600/mo - Voice lessons (prob ~4 month commitment)
$99/mo - access to a trans friendly doctor without gatekeeping
$25ish/mo - medication (after insurance)
$280/mo - therapist

It's so freaking expensive to be trans.

If you have an opportunity to support us from a benefits standpoint, just do it. You may not know your employees are trans, and this is a huge differentiator for trans people.

I list my basic costs below... https://t.co/PO8ndXdsgy

If any of this sounds interesting, I'm happy to talk to anyone who's curious to find out more. I can also connect you with a pre-application call with our CTO @ideasasylum. 

Or, if you're ready to sign up/read the job description, you can find it here: https://t.co/lMx5T2zUPs

6: You *might* just love your job again

Do you wake up thinking about how much you don't want to go to work? I haven't felt that since I've joined Podia.

5:  Challenge yourself and grow

Ever feel like you get stagnant in your skills? We have tons of challenging things we want to build, I can almost bet you it'll push you out of your comfort zone and you'll grow.

4: We're believers in the Rails Way

Our first line of thinking to solve a new problem is to stick within the Rails Way, but when it hurts too much we'll expand out into another tool that helps solve it. Perhaps it's React, but we're careful to not turn into a React heavy project

3: We have a growing design system and 400+ ViewComponents to let us build quickly

We've worked hard over the past year and half to build out our Design System with quite possibly one of the best designers out there: @lukees

2.1: The Customers

The customers we serve have a lot of love for the work we enable them to do. On days when we launch projects, we get a chance to see what the customers are saying about the new stuff. I've never worked somewhere where the _care_ is that high.

2: The Team, The Company

The team is by far the best I've worked on, we're all working to be better every day and we have a no-blame policy for incidents.

The company has A+ players in every department, in Support, Marketing, Content and so forth.

1: We're an all-in-one platform serving creators.

That means there's a ton of variety in what you could be working on, from project to project. It feels like we have many 'products' to work on within our platform. Tons of room to make your impact!

Perhaps you're tired of hearing about our job openings, but if you're a dev with some experience -> senior you might be a good fit!

With the esbuild approach, you stick mostly to the known JS ecosystem approach (a package.json and npm/yarn) then the really nice bits are using Sprockets to serve the outputted file (with fingerprints so caching on cdns can work well etc).

For example, without a package.json managing dependencies, most of the tooling around the ecosystem would have to adapt to help scan for security issues, whereas if you use a package.json/yarn.lock file Depfu/Dependabot etc can scan for known issues with packages.
After sleeping on it and using esbuild-rails briefly last night, I think that's the way to go forward. The importmap stuff is 'neat' but I still have so many issues with the approach.

Then I decided to choose life, and authenticity. 2020 turned into me choosing authenticity and learning about what I truly wanted.

So I chose to transition, consequences be damned. I'm very lucky. I have a good set of friends, family and job. Many folks don't.

Would I loose my friends, family, job, internet followers? Could I face the constant misgendering that society forces people into based on their appearance, clothes, voice etc?

I laid there, not sure what I should do. Unhappy with how I had been living, but scared to go on.

It was dark. I tried more therapy again, it took me 9 months of daily messaging before I said the words to my therapist. I was in bed sick for two days after. I couldn't put myself back in the character I constructed for 27 years.
